@joewalker Per your suggestion last week, here's a version of the "XULStore Using rkv – Proof of Concept" doc.

@bgrins and I chatted about ways to do the conversion. He's previously done this conversion for XBL Replacement newsletters via this process: "paste the contents of this article into http://htmltidy.net/  then take that output and paste it into http://tinyambition.com/h2m/. Then post that to the site, copy the rendered post and paste into mail client then set all fonts to 12px."

In this case, I used [gd2md-html](https://chrome.google.com/webstore/detail/gd2md-html/igffnbdfnodiaphfmfaiiaegmoljbghf) to convert the Google Doc to Markdown. Then I copied the drawings into their own documents and used the "Publish to the web…" feature of Google Drive to publish them to publicly-accessible URLs that I embedded into the Markdown.

I considered exporting the drawings as SVGs, which should theoretically be small enough to be embedded into data: URLs. But Google converts the text to paths, which makes them quite a bit larger. Exported PNGs that are Base64-encoded are also larger than I'd want to embed in a Markdown file. The only other option I know about is to insert the images into a GitHub comment to save them in GitHub, which would be a reasonable alternative.

